<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-03-09T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-03-09T01:00:00-05:00" n="918" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d918">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Tientsin/586: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-03-09T15:00:00+09:00">March 9, 1940—3
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 9—3:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>161. Chungking 113, March 4, 1 p.m.<note n="11" xml:id="d918fn11">Not
                                    printed.</note> Tientsin silver. My British colleague informs me
                                that on March 4 he handed to the Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs a
                                statement of the changes desired by the Chinese Government in the
                                proposed Anglo-Japanese agreement with regard to the Tientsin silver
                                and that “Tani’s immediate reaction was to reject the amendments
                                practically <hi rend="italic">in toto</hi>”. Craigie is to let me
                                have Tani’s reasoned observations when received.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Peiping for Chungking, Tientsin and Shanghai.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>